result.execSummary:
The defendant McKinley M. Mann was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • OWI (2nd) [Modifiers: Penalty - Operating While under the Influence (2nd Offense)], an unclassified misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 346.63(1)(a).
  • Bail Jumping-Misdemeanor, a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 946.49(1)(a).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Statement as to Negotiated Pleas and Diversion Agreement.

DA Fox appeared on behalf of the State.  Defendant appeared in person and with Attorney French.  Defendant plead no contest to counts 1 and amended count 3.  Count  2 dismissed and read in.  Court questions defendant on plea questionnaire, waiver of constitutional rights and elements of the crime to which he plead to.  Prior OWI confirmed by court.  Defendant understands.   Defendant exercised his right to allocution.  Court finds that the defendant freely, voluntarily and intelligently entered his plea, and waived his constitutional rights. Court finds a factual basis exists.  Court finds defendant guilty as plead to.  Defendant declined probation option.  Joint recommendation.  On count 1, court ordered $1379.00 fine, 12 month DL revocation and IID.  60 days jail to start on or before 4/30/15 at 6 pm.  Count 3.  CC & 60 days jail concurrent.

Defendant shall not consume any alcohol unless a physician states in writing that the defendant is alcohol dependent and complete withdrawal could endanger the defendant's health or life. In this case a doctor's excuse must be submitted to the Jackson County Clerk of Court or the Jackson County Jail within 48 hours of the bond being signed. Not to enter into any bars, taverns, liquor stores, liquor department of grocery stores, bar areas of restaurants, or where available for consumption on the premises where the defendant is located.    As a condition of your release, you must be available 24 hours per day, 7 days a week to submit to testing for alcohol when requested by a law enforcement officer or your probation agent. The defendant may submit to an alcohol test at the Jackson County Sheriff's Office or submit to a PBT by a law enforcement officer. Upon request, the defendant shall appear for and submit to testing within two (2) hours of the official's request.
